hypna_example: Because I have mental health issues at the moment, my mind goes very fast all the time. Recently, when I first lay down, there is a wave of negative energy that I have to ground myself through and see past. It comes in the form of chaotic intrusive thoughts. Sometimes they take the form of words, but mostly it's an energy I feel in my head (meditation has helped me see through the content. It gets more intense as I go into an in-between state, where I am not conscious at all, even though I am awake and aware of my unconsciousness. I sometimes pull myself out of it when I become aware of it. Sometimes just past this state, where I am more calm and grounded, I can observe my subconscious thoughts. They take the form of very fast-moving scenes that are bright and I know what they are, but they have no distinct shape that represents real life. It's my brain's interpretation of events, not the actual events themselves. Sometimes they're so fast they flick through 10-20 per second.

I often experience hypnagogic imagery when I'm falling asleep. For example, I sometimes see random faces, shifting patterns, or brief dream-like scenes that don't make much sense. These images appear and disappear quickly, almost like a slideshow in my mind.  I also notice my inner monologue becoming strange and disconnected. I might start thinking about something logical, like what I need to do tomorrow, but then my thoughts suddenly jump to a random childhood memory or a completely unrelated topic, like facts about space or animals.  Sometimes, I experience hypnic jerks, where I feel like I'm falling or tripping on something. Right as I'm drifting off, I'll suddenly get the sensation that I missed a step on a staircase or that I'm falling off a ledge, which makes my body jolt awake.  Occasionally, I also hear faint, imaginary sounds right before I fall asleep-like someone calling my name, a distant doorbell, or a snippet of a conversation that isn't real. It's like my brain is making up random noises as I transition into sleep

hypna_example: It starts with a feeling of soft floating, as if you were suspended in the serene, azure waters of the cove.  Like the brilliant hues of the sunset sky, the day's discussions and chores start to lose their distinct edges.  I might find myself creating intricate patterns with the little, darting fish in place of a to-do list, their movements turning into a sophisticated, flowing dance.   The voices of the folks I spoke to that day echoed the calming rhythm of the waves, and their faces changed and evolved.  However, I concentrate on the underlying feelings-a sense of connection, a moment of humor, a shared challenge-rather than the exact words they used. These emotions turn into the warm, golden light that permeates the scene.The imagery also melds with my physical sensations.  The smooth, giving feel of the milky white sand replaces the sense of my head resting on the cushion.  The blanket's light pressure turns into warm, calm air that has a subtle hint of salt and tropical flowers in it.   My thoughts start to sound more like dreams and less like a straight line.  Even though I'm preparing the presentation for tomorrow, I'm visualizing a group of vibrant starfish listening to me explain it, their arms indicating agreement as I talk.  Or I'm working on a challenging subject at work, and the answer appears to me like a secret path that the ebbing tide has unveiled.It's like looking at the world from a peaceful distance, both present and detached.  Before I'm eventually swept away by sleep, the lines separating my body, my thoughts, and the outside world start to blur, leaving me with a sense of tranquil blending and silent surrender to the flow of consciousness.

hypna_example: When I choose to be aware, I sometime see strange and random scenes. They are so real & intense I wonder if they really happened, are happening or will happen. Once that sticks with me is an American Indian woman who is arguing with someone, as an example. Its like a radio signal, brief snapshots, sounds and images.. In general I ignore them because I've never been able to get enough detail or context to link them to anything real. Only events like these upon waking up have I been able to link to real events in the past, present or future. I've always wondered why my brain does this to me since its very distracting and sometimes causes me to research or dig into things I never would have been interested in. A few have been so intense I wasn't sure whether someone or a movie had planted a suggestion or it was unique to the location I was staying/sleeping at. They are different than dreams because they flow logically or are snapshot like scenes that then jump to something else, like turning the dial on radio stations and suddenly dropping into a frequency. Dreams aren't like this.

routine: This isn't an intentional ritual, but I have noticed that if I'm reading a book or watching a video late into the night, I'm much more likely to "accidentally" fall asleep (as opposed to intentionally closing my eyes and waiting to fall asleep). This is a hypothesis based on experience, but here's what I think the explanation is: sometimes my brain "needs" (or thinks it needs) certain levels of stimulation (maybe that's part of my ADHD?). If I have nothing to think about while falling asleep, I've noticed that sometimes my mind will actively try to invent things to think about, and that mental activity ends up distracting me from actually sleeping. But if I'm reading or watching something that provides that stimulation, my mind can passively absorb it rather than needing to actively generate it, and so my mind can be less active, and thus more easily transition to sleep.
feedback: Especially when it comes to the vividness and detail of something I imagine, and the same for when I'm dreaming or falling asleep, I can "summon up" almost any detail I want, but everything other than that is extremely vague. I can jump between them quite quickly-with the lake landscape, for example, if I force myself to picture the entire scene, I get landscape contours but not much else; but when "just thinking about it," I find myself rapidly "zooming in and out" to different scales, to look at just the tree, then just the shape of the lake with no color or detail, then the surface of the lake with color and texture, then back out. At each level, I can only "see"that level-looking at the lake surface, I lose a sense of the lake's shape, and looking at the entire lake, I lose the sense of its color and texture. It's the same while I'm falling asleep: each detail that is "relevant" to what I'm thinking about is pretty clear, but everything else is extremely indistinct.

feedback: I have recurrent, vivid dreams of the significant places in my life (i.e. my undergraduate campus, or familiar streets and intersections) . Although these places are skewed in my dreams, these places look the same ,albeit skewed every time I dream of them. I could, at this moment draw a basic map of the places I repeatedly go in my dream. There is one intersection where I'm driving but I can't open my eyes - same intersection, same sensation every time. When my children were small I would be getting them dressed, ready for school, but then glance at a corner of the room and realize I was dreaming. Sometimes dreams are so real that I will stare at a wall or a car and force it to be a different color or pattern to test if I'm dreaming. I have had dream that were so vivid and realistic that I try to cover my ears and scream (I literally call them 'scream dreams'). Because I'm trying to scream, I will wake up  squeaking. I could not stay awake in school I would cram the night before an exam but set my alarm for 10 minute naps. During the exam I could remember the words on the pages I had read the night before as though the book was in front of me. There have been many instances where I dreamed a viable solution for a vexing (awake) problem. My overall impression of my dreams is that my mind/memories are filed in labeled folders (house, kids, happiness, sadness). Whatever happens in daytime that is significant enough to remember or forget, has to be put in one of these 'files'. Dreams seem to be the process by which my memories and experiences are categorized so they can be placed in the 'relevant'  file.  I'm from a family of narcoleptics, sleepwalkers, and even sleep talkers (one family member sat up in bed very suddenly and said, "Hooray for the United States of America - leading developer of the Phillips-head screwdriver!", then they laid down again and had no memory of talking in their sleep.). My kids, my sisters and at least one of their kids, talk about our dreams all the time. My mother's father and his brothers and sisters were all vivid dreamers and sleepwalkers. I have started out in my car, headed for a particular shopping center only to wake up/find myself in my mother-in-law's driveway; it's the most common destination when I drive in that direction. If something is misplaced and my family insists that I was the last person to handle the item, I have to ask them what I was doing when I was headed the item. So if I was putting clothes in a drawer, I could open the drawer and find the library book/hair ties or whatever went missing. I know my narcolepsy started when I was in the 3rd grade. Until I was diagnosed and medicated, I felt like I had been trudging through mud in a complete fog my entire life.  Once I was taking stimulants it was as though a heavy curtain was drawn in my brain; I could remember books I had read, recall the citation for I legal case I'd handled years ago.  I will also mention that I have Hyper-mobile Ehler Danlos and have had syncopal episodes my entire life (teasing apart the cataplexy from the syncope was not easy). Droxidopa has changed my life. It is the first, best, only medication to control my syncope. Surprisingly, it hasn't had any effect - positive or negative - on my sleep.

hypna_example: Extremely abstract thoughts usually involving some elements of what I was perceiving before drifting off, e.g. situations, people, sounds. When I was taking medication that made me extremely lethargic I would enter this 'drifting off' phase during daily life and my dreamstate would intertwine with my reality, for example I would suddenly become aware that my lecturer was on a pirate ship and would 'snap back to reality' realising that this can't be real, I must be drifting off. More involuntary and abstract than a day dream, like I was asleep but my dreams merged with my environment. Now my falling asleep phase only really occurs in bed or before napping, and I always find it an inviting comforting psychological space that feels pleasant
feedback: I guess I'd like to reiterate that the 'drifting off' point of sleep for me is my favourite point of sleep, I actually love it and find it really pleasant, sometimes fun, it isn't emotionally intense but does make me feel warm and uplifted in a sense. My thoughts become so abstract it feels like a warm and creative space to be. This is particularly significant for me because I suffer with extremely emotionally intense bad dreams, nightmares and flashback dreams when actually asleep. It's extremely rare that I ever remember 'happy dreams'. Sometimes my dreams disturb me to such an extent that I wake up in floods of tears or having a panic attack, and they felt so vivid that my mental peace can be disturbed for sometimes days. Maybe that's why I love the drifting off stage so much, because it's the only time I actually feel that I am able to enjoy my dreams. I still feel partially conscious/in control and they aren't structured like my nightmares are.
